[2] Cholera - Nigeria (Borno State)
Date: Fri, 21 Oct 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and Daily Trust (Abuja) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200510210484.html>

A cholera epidemic has killed no fewer than 26 people in Biu local
government area of Borno State as health workers and authorities battle to
halt its spread to other parts of the state.
The medical organization, Medecins Sans Frontieres (Doctors Without
Borders), which is currently engaged in providing medical assistance and
drugs to victims of the disease, said the cholera epidemic was caused by
poor sanitation, poor toilet systems, and unclean water.
Daily Trust learnt that the disease started in Marama town of Biu local
government and a number of Fulani settlements close to Biu town before it
spread to Biu town itself. Reports indicate that Galtimari village and the
Biu Senior Science Secondary School are some of the worst-hit areas, with
several casualties as a result of the cholera epidemic.
Doctors Without Borders said they have suggested to Biu local government
authorities that primary and secondary schools in the area be temporarily
closed to halt the spread of the disease. A cholera treatment and
rehabilitation camp has since been set up in Biu town to provide treatment
and drugs to victims, with the charity saying that so far, 327 cases were
reported and admitted, while others whose condition was not serious were
given treatment but not admitted.
Medecins sans Frontieres regretted that many people suffering from the
disease had tried to avoid treatment at the camp because of fasting,
despite encouragement from religious leaders that the sick could seek
medical treatment even during Ramadan.
[Byline: Abdullahi Bego]
