[3] Cholera - Nigeria (Borno State)
Date: Mon, 24 Oct 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Angola Press [edited]
<http://www.angolapress-angop.ao/noticia-e.asp?ID=385829>

A cholera outbreak in Nigeria's northern State of Borno has claimed 12 more
lives from among 250 new cases, the local press reported Sat, 22 Oct
2005. The epidemic of the water-borne disease had spread from the state
capital, Maiduguri, to Biu, some 185 km to the south, where the deaths were
reported. The victims were said to be mainly children and students of the
Government Secondary School in Biu who reportedly drank contaminated water
drawn from hand-dug wells.
Health Commissioner Asabe Vilita Bashir was quoted as saying measures had
been taken by the ministry to contain the outbreak. She said half of the
dead were children below the age of 15, adding that 158 patients had been
treated and discharged from the Biu General Hospital.
The Commissioner advised local communities and the affected secondary
school community to always boil their drinking water, warning that water
from hand-dug wells was not safe for drinking. According to her, the Biu
fatalities brought to 32 the death toll from cholera in the state in 2005,
noting that in July 2005 more than 500 patients were treated for the
disease in Umrari, Jajeri and Gwange neighborhoods of the Maiduguri metropolis.
--
